<p><b>Depth-first search</b> (<b>DFS</b>) is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithm</a> for traversing o=
r searching <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree_data_structure" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tree data structure">tree</a> or <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_(data_structure)" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Graph (data structure)">graph</a> data structures. The algorithm s=
tarts at the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree_(data_structure)=
#Terminology" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tree (data structure)">root no=
de</a> (selecting some arbitrary node as the root node in the case of a gra=
ph) and explores as far as possible along each branch before backtracking. =
Extra memory, usually a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stack_(abs=
tract_data_type)" title=3D"Stack (abstract data type)">stack</a>, is needed=
 to keep track of the nodes discovered so far along a specified branch whic=
h helps in backtracking of the graph.
</p><p>A version of depth-first search was investigated in the 19th century=
 by French mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_P=
ierre_Tr%C3%A9maux" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Charles Pierre Tr=C3=A9m=
aux">Charles Pierre Tr=C3=A9maux</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth-first_search#cite_note-1=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> as a strategy for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maz=
e_solving_algorithm" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Maze solving algorithm"=
>solving mazes</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth-first_search#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Depth-first_search#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
