>stack</a> of vertices on the current search path as well as the set of alr=
eady-visited vertices. Thus, in this setting, the time and space bounds are=
 the same as for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_sea=
rch" title=3D"Breadth-first search">breadth-first search</a> and the choice=
 of which of these two algorithms to use depends less on their complexity a=
nd more on the different properties of the vertex orderings the two algorit=
hms produce.
</p><p>For applications of DFS in relation to specific domains, such as sea=
rching for solutions in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial=
_intelligence" title=3D"Artificial intelligence">artificial intelligence</a=
> or web-crawling, the graph to be traversed is often either too large to v=
isit in its entirety or infinite (DFS may suffer from <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halting_problem" title=3D"Halting problem">non-terminat=
ion</a>). In such cases, search is only performed to a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth-limited_search" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"D=
epth-limited search">limited depth</a>; due to limited resources, such as m=
emory or disk space, one typically does not use data structures to keep tra=
ck of the set of all previously visited vertices. When search is performed =
to a limited depth, the time is still linear in terms of the number of expa=
nded vertices and edges (although this number is not the same as the size o=
f the entire graph because some vertices may be searched more than once and=
 others not at all) but the space complexity of this variant of DFS is only=
 proportional to the depth limit, and as a result, is much smaller than the=
 space needed for searching to the same depth using breadth-first search. F=
or such applications, DFS also lends itself much better to <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heuristics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Heurist=
ics">heuristic</a> methods for choosing a likely-looking branch. When an ap=
propriate depth limit is not known a priori, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Iterative_deepening_depth-first_search" title=3D"Iterative deepe=
ning depth-first search">iterative deepening depth-first search</a> applies=
 DFS repeatedly with a sequence of increasing limits. In the artificial int=
elligence mode of analysis, with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Branching_factor" title=3D"Branching factor">branching factor</a> greater =
than one, iterative deepening increases the running time by only a constant=
 factor over the case in which the correct depth limit is known due to the =
geometric growth of the number of nodes per level.
</p><p>DFS may also be used to collect a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Sample_(statistics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample (statisti=
cs)">sample</a> of graph nodes. However, incomplete DFS, similarly to incom=
plete <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_search#Bias_to=
wards_nodes_of_high_degree" title=3D"Breadth-first search">BFS</a>, is <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bias" title=3D"Bias">biased</a> toward=
s nodes of high <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degree_(graph_theo=
ry)" title=3D"Degree (graph theory)">degree</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Example">Example</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDepth-first_search&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Example"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Depth-First-Search.gif" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7=
/7f/Depth-First-Search.gif/250px-Depth-First-Search.gif" decoding=3D"async"=
 width=3D"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"=
500" data-file-height=3D"500"></a><figcaption>Animated example of a depth-f=
irst search</figcaption></figure>
<p>For the following graph:
</p><p><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fi=
le:Graph.traversal.example.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"A=
n undirected graph with edges AB, BD, BF, FE, AC, CG, AE" src=3D"https://up=
load.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Graph.traversal.example.svg=
/250px-Graph.traversal.example.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"200" he=
ight=3D"162" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"332" data-file-he=
ight=3D"269"></a></span>
</p><p>A depth-first search starting at the node A, assuming that the left =
edges in the shown graph are chosen before right edges, and assuming the se=
arch remembers previously visited nodes and will not repeat them (since thi=
s is a small graph), will visit the nodes in the following order: A, B, D, =
F, E, C, G.  The edges traversed in this search form a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tr%C3%A9maux_tree" title=3D"Tr=C3=A9maux tree">Tr=C3=
=A9maux tree</a>, a structure with important applications in <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_theory" title=3D"Graph theory">graph theor=
y</a>.
Performing the same search without remembering previously visited nodes res=
ults in visiting the nodes in the order A, B, D, F, E, A, B, D, F, E, etc. =
forever, caught in the A, B, D, F, E cycle and never reaching C or G.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iterative_deepening_depth-f=
irst_search" title=3D"Iterative deepening depth-first search">Iterative dee=
pening</a> is one technique to avoid this infinite loop and would reach all=
 nodes.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Output_of_a_depth-first_sea=
rch">Output of a depth-first search</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DDepth-first_search&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
3" title=3D"Edit section: Output of a depth-first search"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Tree_edges.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"=
><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Tree=
_edges.svg/330px-Tree_edges.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" heigh=
t=3D"178" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"412" data-file-heigh=
t=3D"245"></a><figcaption>The four types of edges defined by a spanning tre=
e</figcaption></figure>
<p>The result of a depth-first search of a graph can be conveniently descri=
bed in terms of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spanning_tree_(m=
athematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Spanning tree (mathematics)">sp=
anning tree</a> of the vertices reached during the search. Based on this sp=
anning tree, the edges of the original graph can be divided into three clas=
ses: <b>forward edges</b>, which point from a node of the tree to one of it=
s descendants, <b>back edges</b>, which point from a node to one of its anc=
estors, and <b>cross edges</b>, which do neither. Sometimes <b>tree edges</=
b>, edges which belong to the spanning tree itself, are classified separate=
ly from forward edges. If the original graph is undirected then all of its =
edges are tree edges or back edges.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Vertex_orderings">Vertex or=
derings</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDept=
h-first_search&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Ve=
rtex orderings"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>It is also possible to use depth-first search to linearly order the vert=
ices of a graph or tree. There are four possible ways of doing this:
</p>
<ul><li>A <b>preordering</b> is a list of the vertices in the order that th=
ey were first visited by the depth-first search algorithm. This is a compac=
t and natural way of describing the progress of the search, as was done ear=
lier in this article. A preordering of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Parse_tree" title=3D"Parse tree">expression tree</a> is the express=
ion in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polish_notation" title=3D"P=
olish notation">Polish notation</a>.</li>
<li>A <b>postordering</b> is a list of the vertices in the order that they =
were <i>last</i> visited by the algorithm. A postordering of an expression =
tree is the expression in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reverse_=
Polish_notation" title=3D"Reverse Polish notation">reverse Polish notation<=
/a>.</li>
<li>A <b>reverse preordering</b> is the reverse of a preordering, i.e. a li=
st of the vertices in the opposite order of their first visit. Reverse preo=
rdering is not the same as postordering.</li>
<li>A <b>reverse postordering</b> is the reverse of a postordering, i.e. a =
list of the vertices in the opposite order of their last visit. Reverse pos=
tordering is not the same as preordering.</li></ul>
<p>For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_trees" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Binary trees">binary trees</a> there is additionally <b>i=
n-ordering</b> and <b>reverse in-ordering</b>.
</p><p>For example, when searching the directed graph below beginning at no=
de A, the sequence of traversals is either A B D B A C A or A C D C A B A (=
choosing to first visit B or C from A is up to the algorithm). Note that re=
peat visits in the form of backtracking to a node, to check if it has still=
 unvisited neighbors, are included here (even if it is found to have none).=
 Thus the possible preorderings are A B D C and A C D B, while the possible=
 postorderings are D B C A and D C B A, and the possible reverse postorderi=
ngs are A C B D and A B C D.
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:If-then-else-control-flow-graph.svg" class=3D=
"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"A directed graph with edges AB, BD, AC, C=
D" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/68/If-then=
-else-control-flow-graph.svg/250px-If-then-else-control-flow-graph.svg.png"=
 decoding=3D"async" width=3D"125" height=3D"245" class=3D"mw-file-element" =
data-file-width=3D"125" data-file-height=3D"245"></a></span></dd></dl>
<p>Reverse postordering produces a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Topological_sorting" title=3D"Topological sorting">topological sorting</a>=
 of any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Directed_acyclic_graph" ti=
tle=3D"Directed acyclic graph">directed acyclic graph</a>. This ordering is=
 also useful in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control-flow_graph=
" title=3D"Control-flow graph">control-flow analysis</a> as it often repres=
ents a natural linearization of the control flows. The graph above might re=
present the flow of control in the code fragment below, and it is natural t=
o consider this code in the order A B C D or A C B D but not natural to use=
 the order A B D C or A C D B.
</p>
<pre>if (<b>A</b>) then {
    <b>B</b>
} else {
    <b>C</b>
}
<b>D</b>
</pre>
