<p>A recursive implementation of DFS:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth-first_search#cite_note-=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p>
<pre><b>procedure</b> DFS(<i>G</i>, <i>v</i>) <b>is</b>
    label <i>v</i> as discovered
    <b>for all</b> directed edges from <i>v</i> to <i>w that are</i> <b>in<=
/b> <i>G</i>.adjacentEdges(<i>v</i>) <b>do</b>
        <b>if</b> vertex <i>w</i> is not labeled as discovered <b>then</b>
            recursively call DFS(<i>G</i>, <i>w</i>)
</pre>
<p>A non-recursive implementation of DFS with worst-case space complexity <=
span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xml=
ns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle O(|E|)}=
">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>O</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">|</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>E</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">|</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle O(|E|)}</anno=
tation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/976fe7f1e011d0dcdb3d6163754c877aaad5187f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:6.652ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle O(|=
E|)}"></span>, with the possibility of duplicate vertices on the stack:<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Depth-first_search#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<pre><b>procedure</b> DFS_iterative(<i>G</i>, <i>v</i>) <b>is</b>
    let <i>S</i> be a stack
    <i>S</i>.push(<i>v</i>)
    <b>while</b> <i>S</i> is not empty <b>do</b>
        <i>v</i> =3D <i>S</i>.pop()
        <b>if</b> <i>v</i> is not labeled as discovered <b>then</b>
            label <i>v</i> as discovered
            <b>for all</b> edges from <i>v</i> to <i>w</i> <b>in</b> <i>G</=
i>.adjacentEdges(<i>v</i>) <b>do</b>=20
                <i>S</i>.push(<i>w</i>)
</pre>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Graph.traversal.example.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descr=
iption" title=3D"The example graph, copied from above"><img alt=3D"An undir=
ected graph with edges AB, BD, BF, FE, AC, CG, AE" src=3D"https://upload.wi=
kimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Graph.traversal.example.svg/250px-=
Graph.traversal.example.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"200" height=3D=
"162" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"332" data-file-height=3D=
"269"></a><figcaption>The example graph, copied from above</figcaption></fi=
gure>
<p>These two variations of DFS visit the neighbors of each vertex in the op=
posite order from each other: the first neighbor of <i>v</i> visited by the=
 recursive variation is  the first one in the list of adjacent edges, while=
 in the iterative variation the first visited neighbor is the last one in t=
he list of adjacent edges. The recursive implementation will visit the node=
s from the example graph in the following order: A, B, D, F, E, C, G. The n=
on-recursive implementation will visit the nodes as: A, E, F, B, D, C, G.
</p><p>The non-recursive implementation is similar to <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_search" title=3D"Breadth-first search">br=
eadth-first search</a> but differs from it in two ways:=20
</p>
<ol><li>it uses a stack instead of a queue, and</li>
<li>it delays checking whether a vertex has been discovered until the verte=
x is popped from the stack rather than making this check before adding the =
vertex.</li></ol>
<p>If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">G</span> is=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree_(data_structure)" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tree (data structure)">tree</a>, replacing the queue=
 of the breadth-first search algorithm with a stack will yield a depth-firs=
t search algorithm. For general graphs, replacing the stack of the iterativ=
e depth-first search implementation with a queue would also produce a bread=
th-first search algorithm, although a somewhat nonstandard one.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dep=
th-first_search#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Another possible implementation of iterative depth-first search uses=
 a stack of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iterator" title=3D"Ite=
rator">iterators</a> of the list of neighbors of a node, instead of a stack=
 of nodes. This yields the same traversal as recursive DFS.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth-f=
irst_search#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<pre><b>procedure</b> DFS_iterative(<i>G</i>, <i>v</i>) <b>is</b>
    let <i>S</i> be a stack
    label <i>v</i> as discovered
    <i>S</i>.push(iterator of <i>G</i>.adjacentEdges(<i>v</i>))
    <b>while</b> <i>S</i> is not empty <b>do</b>
        <b>if</b> <i>S</i>.peek().hasNext() <b>then</b>
            <i>w</i> =3D <i>S</i>.peek().next()
            <b>if</b> <i>w</i> is not labeled as discovered <b>then</b>
                label <i>w</i> as discovered
                <i>S</i>.push(iterator of <i>G</i>.adjacentEdges(<i>w</i>))
        <b>else</b>
            <i>S</i>.pop()
</pre>
