er/svg/90a47bca827f9a7b1d72f77316d986207d0096ed" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:16.387ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle O=
=3D(v_{1},\dots ,v_{n})}"></span> be the ordering computed by the standard =
recursive DFS algorithm. This ordering is called the lexicographic depth-fi=
rst search ordering. John Reif considered the complexity of computing the l=
exicographic depth-first search ordering, given a graph and a source. A <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_problem" title=3D"Decision p=
roblem">decision version</a> of the problem (testing whether some vertex <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">u</span> occurs bef=
ore some vertex <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">v=
</span> in this order) is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-comple=
te" title=3D"P-complete"><b>P</b>-complete</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth-first_search=
#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> meaning that it is "a nightmare for <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_algorithm" title=3D"Parallel algorith=
m">parallel processing</a>".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mehlhorn_13-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth-first_search#cite_no=
te-mehlhorn-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"P=
age / location: 189">:=E2=80=8A189=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>A depth-first search ordering (not necessarily the lexicographic one=
), can be computed by a randomized parallel algorithm in the complexity cla=
ss <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NC_(complexity)" title=3D"NC (c=
omplexity)">RNC</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth-first_search#cite_note-14"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 As of 1997, it remained unknown whether a depth-first traversal could be c=
onstructed by a deterministic parallel algorithm, in the complexity class <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NC_(complexity)" title=3D"NC (compl=
exity)">NC</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth-first_search#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
